    summary:"Monica Jacinto Reza, 60, was JPL's Director of the Materials Processing Group and the co-inventor of Mondaloy — a nickel-based superalloy specifically engineered for advanced rocket propulsion that enabled major breakthroughs in US rocket engine technology in 2016, helping reduce US dependence on Russian RD-180 engines (the AR1 development programme). Her alloy work was funded through the AFRL Space Vehicles Directorate — the same directorate Maj. Gen. McCasland commanded from 2001 to 2004. On June 22, 2025 she joined a small hiking group in the San Gabriel Wilderness toward Mount Waterman, departing the day-use area on Angeles Crest Highway at approximately 9:10 a.m. She was not alone: companions were yards ahead on the upper ridge route. She reportedly waved or smiled at the lead hiker from approximately 30–60 feet — and then was gone. Despite extensive air and ground SAR operations (helicopters with FLIR thermal imaging, dog teams, volunteers from multiple counties), no body and no living contact. The Los Angeles County Sheriff's Office classified her at-risk; after the initial intensive search phase ended around June 29, the case moved to the Homicide Bureau Missing Persons Unit — standard LASD procedure for unresolved adult missing persons, not itself evidence of foul play.",
    sections:[
    {heading:"The hike — group context, last sighting, search outcome",body:[
    "She vanished while hiking with others, not on a solitary trek — a detail many early headlines omitted. The route traversed strenuous ridgeline terrain near Mount Waterman at approximately 7,000–8,000 feet elevation. The lead hiker's account, relayed through multiple media, describes turning back within seconds of Reza's last sighting and finding her gone. FLIR thermal sweeps and canine searches covering the immediate pattern returned no result consistent with a person in distress. Her scent trail reportedly ended at a misplaced beanie. No remains have been located.",
    "Aerojet Rocketdyne, NASA, and JPL did not issue the kind of institutional statement that would be expected for a Technical Fellow–level figure with Reza's publication and programme history. The Sentinel Network and subsequent mainstream media coverage noted this silence."
    ]},
    {heading:"Mondaloy and the AFRL connection",body:[
    "Reza's Mondaloy work — a nickel-based superalloy engineered for extreme-temperature performance in rocket engines — was developed under AFRL Space Vehicles Directorate funding during the period when the US was working to eliminate dependence on Russia's RD-180 engine. The AR1 development programme, which Mondaloy enabled, reached key milestones in 2016. McCasland commanded the AFRL Space Vehicles Directorate from 2001 to 2004 — the directorate whose funding streams encompassed advanced materials programmes of this type. The specific personal connection between Reza and McCasland is not documented; the institutional overlap between her funded work and his command of the funding source is documented in press."
    ]},
    {heading:"The JPL corridor — three scientists, one pipeline",body:[
    "Reza is the third of three JPL scientists now gone from the same institutional corridor. Michael David Hicks died July 2023 — no cause, no autopsy. Frank Maiwald died July 2024 — no cause, no autopsy. Monica Reza vanished June 2025. All three worked in overlapping domains of advanced sensing, propulsion materials, and planetary science with dual civilian and defence applications. The Sentinel Network documented this corridor first; NewsNation subsequently named the specific AFRL directorate. Rep. Tim Burchett and Rep. Eric Burlison have both publicly named Reza and McCasland as non-coincidental disappearances."
    ]}],
    off:["Missing person. LASD at-risk classification; extensive SAR; no remains located. Initial response phase ended approximately June 29, 2025; case continued under Homicide Bureau Missing Persons Unit (LASD detectives Shannon Rincon and Richie Sanchez named in later reporting) — standard LASD procedure for unsolved missing adults in LA County. No autopsy (no body). No evidence of foul play confirmed."],
    connections:[
    "Maj. Gen. McCasland: press-reported AFRL funding overlap — her Mondaloy materials work funded under Space Vehicles portfolios he commanded (2001–2004); both vanished under similar circumstances 8 months apart.",
    "Michael David Hicks, Frank Maiwald: same JPL/NASA institutional corridor; advanced sensing and propulsion-adjacent materials.",
    "Anthony Chavez: both vanished in 2025 with personal effects left behind from national security–adjacent research roles."
    ],
