    summary:"Two sitting United States Congressmen have publicly raised the cluster of scientist deaths and disappearances documented in this timeline. Rep. Tim Burchett (R-TN) stated that if the American public knew what he had been briefed on regarding extraterrestrial matters, people would be 'up at night' and the country would come 'unglued.' He explicitly named McCasland and Reza as non-coincidental disappearances. He stated, for the public record: 'I'm not suicidal.' Rep. Eric Burlison (R-MO) formally requested FBI involvement in the disappearances, called the pattern 'deeply concerning,' and said: 'It's remarkable that General McCasland apparently walked out of his home, left all of his devices and never came back. And Monica Reza, she was on a hike as well and mysteriously disappeared. And I've heard of others.' Burchett put the broader situation plainly: 'This has had a real chilling effect. People don't want to talk about this issue of Unidentified Flying Objects anymore, and it's kind of difficult to get to people because they are afraid.' A sitting US Congressman, briefed at the classified level on UAP programmes, publicly stating for the record that he is not suicidal: that is what this entry documents.",
    off:["Both are sitting US Congressmen. Their public statements are documented in multiple media outlets. Neither has produced classified evidence publicly, named a specific perpetrator, or drawn a proven operational chain connecting the individual cases. Their role in this timeline is as political data points — the moment this pattern moved from Substack into formal Congressional record — not as evidentiary sources. Burchett's 'I'm not suicidal' statement is a matter of public record in multiple published interviews."],
